\f0\b\fs44 \cf2 The Ten Questions
\f1\b0\fs28 \cf2 \
\
A healthy democracy gives its citizens not only the right to choose their leaders, but the tools to judge them. In a time when noise overwhelms substance and performance often disguises intent, voters need a simple way to cut through ambiguity. The Ten Questions exist for this purpose. They are not ideological tests or partisan traps. They are civic instruments\'97questions that reveal whether a candidate understands the responsibilities of self-government and is prepared to uphold them when pressure mounts.\
\
These questions draw directly from the architecture of this book: the promises a republic must keep, the imperatives that allow it to function, the deliverables that measure whether it serves its people, and the moral floor that determines whether power is used for the common good. Each question points to one essential element of democratic stewardship. A candidate who can answer them with clarity is a candidate prepared to govern. A candidate who evades them exposes a weakness the republic can no longer afford.\
\
The power of these questions lies in their simplicity. They can be asked at a town hall, sent in an email, raised at a community meeting, or posed in a conversation with a neighbor considering a run for office. They require no expertise to ask and no performance to interpret. They reveal whether someone seeking authority understands that they are asking for the public\'92s trust\'97and whether they are ready to earn it.\
\
The Ten Questions:\
\
